The cost-effectiveness study from 2001 was based on the assumption that the section near the border and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains were entering traffic at the same time.
At the time of the test, it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Mountains would not be opened on the original date.
This reduces the aforementioned EIRR values.
At 31.12.2005, the cost of both sections was €897 million without VAT, which is 27.4% higher than the economic impact of 2001.
In addition, there is a risk that section 0805 will have a different and more complex route, which would affect the economic efficiency of the project.
The economic assessment showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically justified with a daily traffic volume of at least 18 000 cars per day in 2010. The forecast for 2008 predicted 22 940 cars per day.
However, a study on diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Central Mountains assumes a traffic volume of 12,600 to 13,750 cars per day in 2007, which is below the economic efficiency limit.
Higher traffic on the routes, which are to replace the missing section by the Central Bohemian Mountains, is highly likely to lead to congestion and thus to higher external costs, which were not taken into account in the original economic performance analysis.
The above-mentioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the near-border section of the D 8 will not be reached.
The construction of the near-border section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomic.
There were also cost increases in the construction of the A 17, as in the construction of the two sections of the D 8 mentioned above.
In the context of the overall economic assessment of the 1992 Federal Road Plan, the Federal Ministry of Transport assumed investment costs of around €320 million.
This gave it a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.
In the meantime, costs have increased to around €670 million and the benefit / cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.
The BRH had tested the economic efficiency of the planning and construction of the A 17 motorway in the years 2003 to 2005, regardless of the parallel tests with the NK.
He noted that the authority in charge of the permit requested an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of A 17.
In the course of the test, the BRH was able to convince the Federal Ministry and the road construction administration of the superfluity of the landscape tunnel.
This avoided €10 million in construction costs and €150,000 in annual operating costs.
When examining the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction was inadequately prepared.
The following example makes this clear:
During the planning phase, the road administration refused to record the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschener wall, as it was difficult to access.
It was only when the tunnel drift reached the wall that she caught up with it.
This showed that the rock was more weathered than assumed in the tender.
Elaborate measures such as anchoring, injections and rock-impact protection networks for around €3.3 million became necessary.
Not only did the road administration bear the costs for additional services, which were already required, such as securing the Dölzschener wall, but also for those that would not have been necessary if the building had been properly prepared.
This includes expenses due to disturbed construction processes (€3.2 million), additional training of the driving team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of the construction period (€7 million).
These additional expenses of around €10.7 million are not offset by any lasting added value.
The BRH has taken these and other measures as an opportunity to ask the Federal Ministry to better exercise the specialist supervision it has for major road construction measures.
In this context, it should be urged that the road management authorities introduce quality assurance systems.
Advantages of cooperation for BRH and NK The cooperation met the expectations of both courts.
The BRH obtained knowledge on the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both audit bodies have developed a database of bridge and tunnel prices that will help in future audits.
The NCA found that the main structural parameters for the bridges, tunnels and carriageway of the D 8 are not different from those of the A 17.
The auditors of both audit courts involved in the cooperation have gained valuable experience, which will be useful in future audits.
